properties.description:
Woodlands donated in memory of Joseph Skinner, an early proponent of conservation in Groton. Includes a pond, a large erratic known as “Bull Rock” at the edge of Whitney (Cow) Pond, and a network of trails. This is a very nice hiking area with several miles worth of trails. Trail difficulty is easy with some moderatly difficult hills. Trail conditions are good, though they are rocky as this used to be a logging area. Some nice scenic areas through wetlands and by Whitney Pond.
For a detailed map of this trail, Click here

properties.description:
Sitting prominently in a 1,500-acre block of contiguous protected open space, 360-acre Surrenden Farm is Groton's highest conservation priority. With 3/4 mile of Nashua River frontage, forest and scenic rolling hayfields, Surrenden Farm is one of the largest remaining unprotected landscapes in town. In 2006, TPL worked with the Town of Groton and the Groton Conservation Trust to assemble the funds required to acquire the property.

Forest, fields, and wetlands. The forest is managed for timber and wildlife as well as for quiet recreation. This large area of open space provides protection for the Groton municipal water supply. 3.4 miles of trails north of Rocky Hill Rd. Mostly flat with some very steep and rocky hills. Some wet areas. 1.8 miles of trails to south of Rocky Hill Rd. and west of Old Dunstable. Mostly very difficult mountain bike trails but nice hiking. 2.5 miles of trails east of Old Dunstable Rd. Mostly flat with a few moderate hills.
